{"title_page": "Geoffrey Streatfeild", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Geoffrey Streatfeild\n|birth_date={{birth year and age|1975}}\n|birth_place=[[London]], England\n}}\n'''Geoffrey Streatfeild''' (born 1975) is an English actor in film, television, stage and radio. He is a member of the [[Streatfeild family]].\n\n==Early life==\nStreatfeild was born in London, and trained at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] (RADA). He has a brother Richard, older by two years.\n\n==Career==\nHis notable film and TV roles include ''[[The Other Boleyn Girl (2003 film)|The Other Boleyn Girl]]'' and ''[[Kinky Boots (film)|Kinky Boots]]''. He also appeared in the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]'s \"Histories\" company in 2007-08 as Prince Hal/Henry V (''[[Henry IV Part One]]'', ''[[Henry IV Part Two]]'' and ''[[Henry V (play)|Henry V]]''), Suffolk (''Henry VI Parts [[Henry VI Part 1|I]] and [[Henry VI Part 2|II]]''), Rivers (''[[Henry VI Part III]]'' and ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'').<ref>[http://www.rsc.org.uk/content/5673.aspx Histories ensemble - Geoffrey Streatfeild]</ref>\n\nHis elder brother Richard Streatfeild, as a serving Major in the [[Rifles troops|Rifles]], advised Geoffrey on military life for his roles in ''Henry V'' and ''Journey's End''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/the_way_we_live/article3861348.ece|title=Geoffrey Streatfeild and his brother Richard|date=4 May 2008|work=[[Sunday Times]] | location=London}}</ref> Streatfeild joined the cast of ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]'' for its final series in 2011, playing the character of Calum Reed, a Junior Case Officer at MI5 until its end.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006mf4b/characters/calumreed \"Calum Reed\"] Spooks Profile, BBC.</ref> In 2012 Streatfeild joined the cast of the popular BBC2 political satire ''[[The Thick of It]]'' as the \"Inbetweener\" junior minister in DoSac. In 2015 he reprised his role as Calum Reed in the spy film ''[[Spooks: The Greater Good]]''.\n\n==Selected credits==\n===Stage===\n*''Eigengrau'' ([[Bush Theatre]]) by [[Penelope Skinner]]<ref>Eigengrau {{cite web |url=http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/production/eigengrau/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110821105432/http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/production/eigengrau/ |archivedate=21 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*''[[The History Boys]]'' ([[Royal National Theatre|National]], tour) by [[Alan Bennett]]\n*''[[The Bacchae|Bacchai]]'' ([[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]])\n*''Mountain Language'' ([[Royal Court Theatre|Royal Court]])\n*''[[Journey\u2019s End]]'', as Stanhope ([[Comedy Theatre]]) by [[R. C. Sherriff]]\n*''[[Nathan the Wise]]'' ([[Chichester Festival Theatre|Chichester]])\n*''[[Merchant of Venice]]'' (Chichester) by [[William Shakespeare]]\n*''[[Macbeth]]'' ([[Sheffield Crucible]]) by [[William Shakespeare]]\n*''[[My Night with Reg]]'' ([[Donmar Warehouse]] and [[Apollo Theatre]]) by [[Kevin Elyot]]\n*''[[The Beaux' Stratagem]]'' (National Theatre) by [[George Farquhar]]\n*''Young Chekhov [[Ivanov (play)|Ivanov]]'' (National Theatre) by [[Anton Chekhov]]\n*''Young Chekhov [[The Seagull]]'' (National Theatre) by [[Anton Chekhov]]\n*''[[Cell Mates (play)|Cell Mates]]'' ([[Hampstead Theatre]]) by [[Simon Gray]] in December 2017\n\n===TV===\n*''[[Sword of Honour]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Love in a Cold Climate (TV serial)|Love in a Cold Climate]]'' (2001)\n*''[[The Other Boleyn Girl (2003 film)|The Other Boleyn Girl]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Elizabeth I (TV miniseries)|Elizabeth I]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Twenty Thousand Streets Under the Sky]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Midsomer Murders]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Ashes to Ashes (TV series)|Ashes to Ashes]]'' (2009) - As 'New Arrival'\n*''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]'' (2011)\n*''[[The Thick of It]]'' (2012)\n*''[[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown]]'' (2016) - as Edward IV, (in 2 episodes: Henry VI part II and Richard III)\n\n===Film===\n*''[[Match Point]]''\n*''[[Kinky Boots (film)|Kinky Boots]]''\n*''[[City Slacker]]''<ref name=\"int\">{{cite web |title=Interview: Fiona Gillies talks about City Slacker |date=13 September 2013 |first=John-Paul |last=Stephenson |url=http://www.gigglebeats.co.uk/2013/09/interview-fiona-gillies-talks-about-city-slacker/ |work=Giggle Beats |accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref>\n*''[[Spooks: The Greater Good]]'' (2015)\n\n===Radio===\n*''[[The Officers' Ward (novel)|The Officers' Ward]]''\n*''[[Jeremy Mortimer#David Copperfield|David Copperfield]]'', [[BBC Radio 4]] [[Woman's Hour Drama]], 5\u201330 December 2005\n*''[[Brideshead Revisited]]''\n*''[[Toby Swift#The Waterbucks|The Waterbucks]]'', [[BBC Radio 4]] [[Afternoon Play]], 23 November 2005\n*''Marks''\n*''Richard III''\n*''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]''\n*''Nathan The Wise''\n*''The History Boys''\n*''[[Palliser novels|The Pallisers]]''\n*''The Ballad of Shane O\u2019Neill''\n*''[[Arnold Wesker|Shylock]]''\n*''[[Toby Swift#Success Story|Success Story]]'', [[BBC Radio 4]] [[Afternoon Play]], 6 March 2009\n*''[[A Taste for Death (Modesty Blaise)|Modesty Blaise - A Taste for Death]]'', [[BBC Radio 4]] [[Woman's Hour Drama|15 Minute Drama]], 17\u201321 December 2012\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1127608}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Streatfeild}}\n[[Category:Streatfeild family|Geoffrey]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male radio actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Geoffrey Streatfeild\n|birth_date={{birth year and age|1975}}\n|birth_place=[[London]], England\n}}\n'''Geoffrey Streatfeild''' (born 1975) is an English actor in film, television, stage and radio. He is a member of the [[Streatfeild family]].\n\n==Early life==\nStreatfeild was born in London, and trained at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] (RADA). He has a brother Richard, older by two years.\n\n==Career==\nHis notable film and TV roles include ''[[The Other Boleyn Girl (2003 film)|The Other Boleyn Girl]]'' and ''[[Kinky Boots (film)|Kinky Boots]]''. He also appeared in the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]'s \"Histories\" company in 2007-08 as Prince Hal/Henry V (''[[Henry IV Part One]]'', ''[[Henry IV Part Two]]'' and ''[[Henry V (play)|Henry V]]''), Suffolk (''Henry VI Parts [[Henry VI Part 1|I]] and [[Henry VI Part 2|II]]''), Rivers (''[[Henry VI Part III]]'' and ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'').<ref>[http://www.rsc.org.uk/content/5673.aspx Histories ensemble - Geoffrey Streatfeild]</ref>\n\nHis elder brother Richard Streatfeild, as a serving Major in the [[Rifles troops|Rifles]], advised Geoffrey on military life for his roles in ''Henry V'' and ''Journey's End''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/the_way_we_live/article3861348.ece|title=Geoffrey Streatfeild and his brother Richard|date=4 May 2008|work=[[Sunday Times]] | location=London}}</ref> Streatfeild joined the cast of ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]'' for its final series in 2011, playing the character of Calum Reed, a Junior Case Officer at MI5 until its end.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006mf4b/characters/calumreed \"Calum Reed\"] Spooks Profile, BBC.</ref> In 2012 Streatfeild joined the cast of the popular BBC2 political satire ''[[The Thick of It]]'' as the \"Inbetweener\" junior minister in DoSac. In 2015 he reprised his role as Calum Reed in the spy film ''[[Spooks: The Greater Good]]''.\n\n==Selected credits==\n===Stage===\n*''Eigengrau'' ([[Bush Theatre]]) by [[Penelope Skinner]]<ref>Eigengrau {{cite web |url=http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/production/