.pdf|title=Dr. Michael Schumann - CV|last=|first=|date=|website=European Finance Forum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Adam Selipskyas, CEO of [[Tableau Software]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://finance.yahoo.com/news/tableau-software-appoints-former-amazon-204608647.html|title=Tableau Software Appoints Former Amazon Exec as CEO|last=|first=|date=2018-07-23|website=Yahoo Finance|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Scott Setrakian, co-founder of [[Applied Predictive Technologies]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siepr.stanford.edu/events/speakers/scott-setrakian|title=Scott Setrakian {{!}} SIEPR|last=|first=|date=|website=Stanford Institute for Economic Policy Research|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Premal Shah]], American entrepreneur and co-founder of [[Kiva]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20080509005071/en/Oliver-Wyman-Announces-Strategic-Alliance-Kiva-Worlds|title=Oliver Wyman Announces Strategic Alliance with Kiva, the World's Leading Person-to-Person Micro-Lending Website|last=|first=|date=2008-05-09|website=Business Wire|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*[[Adrian Slywotzky]], award-winning American author and economist\n*[[Larry Tanz]], American entertainment industry executive\n*Herbert \"Peter\" Temple III, former director of the [[Boston Arts Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vineyardgazette.com/obituaries/2012/10/24/herbert-m-temple-3rd-91-was-longtime-vineyard-visitor|title=Herbert M. Temple 3rd, 91, Was Longtime Vineyard Visitor|last=|first=|date=2012-10-24|website=The Vineyard Gazette|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and co-owner of [[Brattle Theatre|Brattle Theater]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2012/11/04/peter-temple-business-consultant-also-acted-ran-sheep-farm-millis/2IFVHPvoFoPVjvkRBbFxhL/story.html|title=Peter Temple, 91; business consultant, actor, sheep farmer|last=Werthmann|first=Melissa M.|last2=|date=2012-11-04|website=The Boston Globe|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last3=|last4=|first4=}}</ref>\n*[[Miqdaad Versi]], assistant Secretary General to the [[Muslim Council of Britain]]\n* [[Jamie Whyte]], leader of [[ACT New Zealand]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11198243|title=Michele Hewitson interview: Jamie Whyte|last=|first=|date=2014-02-08|website=New Zealand Herald|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*Stephen Wilcke, CEO of the British [[Asset Protection Agency]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hall|first=James|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/7791144/Revealed-Salaries-of-the-Citys-top-civil-servants.html|title=Revealed: Salaries of the City's top civil servants|date=2010-06-01|work=The Telegraph|access-date=|url-status=live|last2=Mason|first2=Rowena|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n*[[Debbie Wosskow]], British entrepreneur and angel investor\n*[[Andrew Youn]], founder of [[One Acre Fund]]\n* [[Jeffrey Zients]], former Director of the [[National Economic Council (United States)|United States National Economic Council]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.oliverwyman.com Oliver Wyman]\n\n{{Consulting}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Consulting]]\n[[Category:International management consulting firms]]\n[[Category:Management consulting firms of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Pereneph", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliver_Wyman"}
{"title_page": "A5199 road", "text_new": "{{short description|Road in England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=5199\n|image=Welford High Street.JPG\n|image_notes=The A5199 through Welford indicating why the double-digit A50 was downgraded to four-digit\n|subtype=minor\n|length_mi=\n|direction_a= North\n|terminus_a = [[Leicester|City of Leicester]] ([[Southfields, Leicester|Freemen's]])\n|direction_b= South\n|terminus_b = [[Kingsthorpe]], [[Northampton|Northampton Borough]]\n|junction   = <span class=\"nowrap\">[[Image:UK road A594.svg|x19px|alt=A594|link=]] [[A594 road (Leicester)|A594 road]]</span><br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|563|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|4304|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|14|name1= }} Junction 1<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|508|name1= }}\n|destinations= [[Leicester]], [[Northampton]]\n}}\n\n'''The A5199 road''' is the direct road from [[Northampton]] to [[Leicester]] in [[England]]. It was formerly part of the [[A50 road|A50]] [[trunk road]] that ran from [[Bedfordshire]] to [[Lancashire]].  For most of its length it is known as the '''Welford Road''', except for small stretches near [[Welford, Northamptonshire|Welford]] where it is known as High Street and '''Northampton Road'''.\n\nAs its course is broadly parallel and near to the [[M1 motorway]] it is very much lacking in modern features such as [[Bypass (road)|bypasses]] which is why it was classified downwards when the [[A14 road (Great Britain)|A14 road]], which it crosses at Junction 1, was built as a link between the M1/M6 junction and the East Coast ports.\n\n== Settlements on the A5199 ==\nThe road commences in the [[Southfields, Leicester|Freemen's]] district of inner city [[Leicester]] at the junction with the [[A594 road (Leicester)|A594 Leicester Central Ring]].\n\n;North to South\n[[Leicester|City of Leicester]]\n*[[Clarendon Park, Leicester|Clarendon Park]]\n*[[Knighton, Leicestershire|Knighton]]\n[[Leicestershire]]\n*[[Wigston Fields]]\n*[[Wigston]]\n*[[Kilby Bridge]]\n*[[Husbands Bosworth]]\n[[Northamptonshire]]\n*[[Welford, Northamptonshire|Welford]]\n*[[Thornby, Northamptonshire|Thornby]]\n*[[Creaton]]\n*[[Spratton]]\n*[[Chapel Brampton]]\n\nIt terminates at a junction with the [[A508 road|A508]] in the Northampton suburb of [[Kingsthorpe]].\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category inline|A5199 road (England)}}\n\n{{GB A road zone 5}}\n\n{{coord|52.4434|N|1.05739|W|type:landmark_region:GB_dim:30000|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:5-5199}}\n[[Category:Roads in England]]\n[[Category:Transport in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:Transport in Northamptonshire]]\n\n\n{{England-road-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Road in England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=5199\n|image=Welford High Street.JPG\n|image_notes=The A5199 through Welford indicating why the double-digit A50 was downgraded to four-digit\n|subtype=minor\n|length_mi=\n|direction_a= North\n|terminus_a = [[Leicester|City of Leicester]] ([[Southfields, Leicester|Freemen's]])\n|direction_b= South\n|terminus_b = [[Kingsthorpe]], [[Northampton|Northampton Borough]]\n|junction   = <span class=\"nowrap\">[[Image:UK road A594.PNG|x19px|alt=A594|link=]] [[A594 road (Leicester)|A594 road]]</span><br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|563|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|4304|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|14|name1= }} Junction 1<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|508|name1= }}\n|destinations= [[Leicester]], [[Northampton]]\n}}\n\n'''The A5199 road''' is the direct road from [[Northampton]] to [[Leicester]] in [[England]]. It was formerly part of the [[A50 road|A50]] [[trunk road]] that ran from [[Bedfordshire]] to [[Lancashire]].  For most of its length it is known as the '''Welford Road''', except for small stretches near [[Welford, Northamptonshire|Welford]] where it is known as High Street and '''Northampton Road'''.\n\nAs its course is broadly parallel and near to the [[M1 motorway]] it is very much lacking in modern features such as [[Bypass (road)|bypasses]] which is why it was classified downwards when the [[A14 road (Great Britain)|A14 road]], which it crosses at Junction 1, was built as a link between the M1/M6 junction and the East Coast ports.\n\n== Settlements on the A5199 ==\nThe road commences in the [[Southfields, Leicester|Freemen's]] district of inner city [[Leicester]] at the junction with the [[A594 road (Leicester)|A594 Leicester Central Ring]].\n\n;North to South\n[[Leicester|City of Leicester]]\n*[[Clarendon Park, Leicester|Clarendon Park]]\n*[[Knighton, Leicestershire|Knighton]]\n[[Leicestershire]]\n*[[Wigston Fields]]\n*[[Wigston]]\n*[[Kilby Bridge]]\n*[[Husbands Bosworth]]\n[[Northamptonshire]]\n*[[Welford, Northamptonshire|Welford]]\n*[[Thornby, Northamptonshire|Thornby]]\n*[[Creaton]]\n*[[Spratton]]\n*[[Chapel Brampton]]\n\nIt terminates at a junction with the [[A508 road|A508]] in the Northampton suburb of [[Kingsthorpe]].\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category inline|A5199 road (England)}}\n\n{{GB A road zone 5}}\n\n{{coord|52.4434|N|1.05739|W|type:landmark_region:GB_dim:30000|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:5-5199}}\n[[Category:Roads in England]]\n[[Category:Transport in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:Transport in Northamptonshire]]\n\n\n{{England-road-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rschen7754", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File:UK road A594.PNG\u2192File:UK road A594.svgsvg", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A5199_road"}
{"title_page": "A426 road", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=426\n|image=Market Street, Lutterworth.jpg\n|image_notes=The A426 in Lutterworh\n|subtype=minor\n|length_mi=29\n|direction_a= North\n|terminus_a = [[Leicester]]\n|direction_b= South\n|terminus_b = [[Southam]]\n|junction   = <span class=\"nowrap\">[[Image:UK road A594.svg|x19px|alt=A594|link=]] [[A594 road (Leicester)|A594 road]]</span><br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|563|name1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|4303|name1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|5|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|M|6|dab1=Great Britain}} J1<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|428|name1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|4071|name1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|423|name1= }}\n|destinations= [[Leicester]], [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]]\n}}\n\nThe '''A426 road''' is a road in [[England]] which runs from the city of [[Leicester]] to the market town of [[Southam]] in [[Warwickshire]] via the towns of [[Lutterworth]] and [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]].\n\n==History==\n{{ref-improve|section|date=November 2018}}\nUntil the [[M1 motorway]] was completed in the 1960s this route formed the main route between Rugby and Leicester, now much quieter as all but local traffic uses the motorway. However, the local traffic has increased as [[Magna Park]], a prominent East Midlands warehouse facility, has developed close to Lutterworth. [[Broughton Astley]], a couple of miles north-west of [[Dunton Bassett]] and other local villages can often become congested with goods vehicles en route between Magna Park, the [[M1 motorway]] and the [[M6 Motorway]]. At rush hours the road can become gridlocked and reduced to less than 40&nbsp;mph, particularly as agricultural traffic frequently uses the stretch. For this reason, journeys between Blaby and Rugby during rush hour can take much longer than anticipated.\n\nThe A426 crosses the route of the former [[A45 road|A45]] in [[Dunchurch]], this would have formed one of the main routes between the Midlands and South East. Dunchurch is now bypassed to the South by the [[M45 motorway]], and the A426 no longer meets the A45\n\n==Route==\n\nThe A426 starts on the [[Leicester]] Inner Ring Road, heading South through the suburbs of the City, crossing the Outer Ring Road and bypassing the village of [[Blaby]]. It crosses over the [[M1 motorway|M1]] which it runs parallel to for the next {{convert|10|mi|km}} or so. The road becomes rural in nature until entering the small town of [[Lutterworth]] and crossing the A4303 Southern Bypass. A further {{convert|2|mi|km}} south and it crosses the [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5]] [[Watling Street]] at a roundabout and eventually the [[M6 motorway|M6]] junction 1. It starts a descent into [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]] as a dual carriageway with 5 local access roundabouts. Approaching the Town Centre the road becomes single carriageway again and crosses under the [[West Coast Main Line]]. It passes the main Town Centre to the West and heads Southwards out of the town towards [[Dunchurch]] after which it passes over the [[M45 motorway|M45]] and once again becomes a rural road for its final length to terminate on the [[A423 road|A423]] [[Southam]] bypass.\n\n==Former routes==\nThe A426, compared to other routes is a relatively untouched road, with only a single bypass:\n* The road used to travel through the village of [[Blaby]], now bypassed\n\n==Bus corridor==\nA controversial decision to allow a bus corridor to be constructed on the A426 from [[Blaby]] into [[Leicester]] was given the go ahead despite heavy local opposition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/A426-bus-lanes-plan-given-ahead/story-17627547-detail/story.html#axzz2WAz5x8tB |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130716012310/http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/A426-bus-lanes-plan-given-ahead/story-17627547-detail/story.html#axzz2WAz5x8tB |archive-date=16 July 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{GB A road zone 4}}\n\n{{coord|52.43851|N|1.20197|W|type:landmark_region:GB_dim:20000|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:4-0426}}\n[[Category:Roads in England]]\n[[Category:Transport in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:Transport in Leicester]]\n[[Category:Roads in Warwickshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=426\n|image=Market Street, Lutterworth.jpg\n|image_notes=The A426 in Lutterworh\n|subtype=minor\n|length_mi=29\n|direction_a= North\n|terminus_a = [[Leicester]]\n|direction_b= South\n|terminus_b = [[Southam]]\n|junction   = <span class=\"nowrap\">[[Image:UK road A594.PNG|x19px|alt=A594|link=]] [[A594 road (Leicester)|A594 road]]</span><br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|563|name1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|4303|name1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|5|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|M|6|dab1=Great Britain}} J1<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|428|name1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|4071|name1= }}<br>{{jct|country=GBR|A|423|name1= }}\n|destinations= [[Leicester]], [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]]\n}}\n\nThe '''A426 road''' is a road in [[England]] which runs from the city of [[Leicester]] to the market town of [[Southam]] in [[Warwickshire]] via the towns of [[Lutterworth]] and [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]].\n\n==History==\n{{ref-improve|section|date=November 2018}}\nUntil the [[M1 motorway]] was completed in the 1960s this route formed the main route between Rugby and Leicester, now much quieter as all but local traffic uses the motorway. However, the local traffic has increased as [[Magna Park]], a prominent East Midlands warehouse facility, has developed close to Lutterworth. [[Broughton Astley]], a couple of miles north-west of [[Dunton Bassett]] and other local villages can often become congested with goods vehicles en route between Magna Park, the [[M1 motorway]] and the [[M6 Motorway]]. At rush hours the road can become gridlocked and reduced to less than 40&nbsp;mph, particularly as agricultural traffic frequently uses the stretch. For this reason, journeys between Blaby and Rugby during rush hour can take much longer than anticipated.\n\nThe A426 crosses the route of the former [[A45 road|A45]] in [[Dunchurch]], this would have formed one of the main routes between the Midlands and South East. Dunchurch is now bypassed to the South by the [[M45 motorway]], and the A426 no longer meets the A45\n\n==Route==\n\nThe A426 starts on the [[Leicester]] Inner Ring Road, heading South through the suburbs of the City, crossing the Outer Ring Road and bypassing the village of [[Blaby]]. It crosses over the [[M1 motorway|M1]] which it runs parallel to for the next {{convert|10|mi|km}} or so. The road becomes rural in nature until entering the small town of [[Lutterworth]] and crossing the A4303 Southern Bypass. A further {{convert|2|mi|km}} south and it crosses the [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5]] [[Watling Street]] at a roundabout and eventually the [[M6 motorway|M6]] junction 1. It starts a descent into [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]] as a dual carriageway with 5 local access roundabouts. Approaching the Town Centre the road becomes single carriageway again and crosses under the [[West Coast Main Line]]. It passes the main Town Centre to the West and heads Southwards out of the town towards [[Dunchurch]] after which it passes over the [[M45 motorway|M45]] and once again becomes a rural road for its final length to terminate on the [[A423 road|A423]] [[Southam]] bypass.\n\n==Former routes==\nThe A426, compared to other routes is a relatively untouched road, with only a single bypass:\n* The road used to travel through the village of [[Blaby]], now bypassed\n\n==Bus corridor==\nA controversial decision to allow a bus corridor to be constructed on the A426 from [[Blaby]] into [[Leicester]] was given the go ahead despite heavy local opposition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/A426-bus-lanes-plan-given-ahead/story-17627547-detail/story.html#axzz2WAz5x8tB |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130716012310/http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/A426-bus-lanes-plan-given-ahead/story-17627547-detail/story.html#axzz2WAz5x8tB |archive-date=16 July 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{GB A road zone 4}}\n\n{{coord|52.43851|N|1.20197|W|type:landmark_region:GB_dim:20000|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:4-0426}}\n[[Category:Roads in England]]\n[[Category:Transport in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:Transport in Leicester]]\n[[Category:Roads in Warwickshire]]\n", "name_user": "Rschen7754", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File:UK road A594.PNG\u2192File:UK road A594.svgsvg", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A426_road"}
{"title_page": "A595 road", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=595\n|length_mi=\n|direction_a= North\n|terminus_a = [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]]\n|direction_b= South\n|terminus_b = [[Dalton-in-Furness]]<br>{{coord|54.1639|-3.1888|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=A595 road (southern end)}}\n|junction   = {{jct|country=GBR|A|7|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|596|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|591|name1= }}<br />[[File:UK road A594.svg|50px|alt=A594]] [[A594 road (Cumbria)|A594 road]]<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|5086|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|66|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|597|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|5094|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|5093|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|5093|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|593|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|5092|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|590|name1= }}\n|destinations= [[Workington]]<br>[[Whitehaven]]<br>[[Barrow-in-Furness]]\n}}\n\nThe '''A595''' is a [[primary route]] in [[Cumbria]], in [[Northern England]] that starts in [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], passes through [[Whitehaven]] and goes close to [[Workington]], [[Cockermouth]] and [[Wigton]]. It passes [[Sellafield]] and [[Ravenglass]] before ending at the [[Dalton-in-Furness]] by-pass, in southern Cumbria, where it joins the [[A590 road|A590]] trunk road. The road is mostly [[single carriageway]], apart from in central Carlisle, where it passes the [[Carlisle Castle|castle]] as a busy [[dual carriageway]] road named Castle Way, and prior to that as Bridge Street and Church Street, where it passes close to the [[McVitie's]] or [[Carr's]] [[biscuit]] factory. The Lillyhall bypass is also dual carriageway.\n\nThe road in the [[Whitehaven]] area was laid out in the 1930s and the A595 was designated a trunk route in 1946. It was detrunked in 1998, apart from an {{Convert|18|mi|adj=on}} section between Little Clifton and [[Calder Bridge]]. This section represents the route from [[Sellafield]] to the [[A66 road (England)|A66]].\n\nAt Duddon Bridge and at Dove Ford near Grizebeck the road passes through farmyards.\n\n==Route==\n\n===Northern section===\nThe {{convert|85|mi|adj=on}} long A595 is also known as the Cumbrian Coast Road despite much of the road following in an inland route. Starting at the Hardwicke Circus roundabout junction with the [[A7 road (Great Britain)|A7]] in [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], it forms a short section of dual carriageway known as Castle Way. This section passes [[Carlisle Castle]] and [[Tullie House]]. Prior to the construction of Castle Way, the road was split in 2 at this section. It then continues over Caldew Bridge to a thoroughfare called Caldewgate, before arriving at a roundabout close to the [[McVitie's]] factory in the city centre. It then follows the route of Wigton Road through the district of Morton, before reaching the outer boundary of Carlisle. At this point it passes the start point of the Carlisle Northern Development Route, where construction work commenced in 2009. This route is the A689.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\">http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A595</ref> A further roundabout was constructed in 2011 around 1 mile south of Carlisle in anticipation of increased traffic for a nearby garden centre development.\n\nThe route continues in a south-westerly direction until it reaches a roundabout on the outskirts of [[Thursby]] at a junction with [[A596 road|A596]]. The roads previously met in the centre of the village of Thursby, before the construction of the Thursby bypass in the 1980s. The A595 runs largely parallel to [[A596]], before the [[A596]] terminates in Workington.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nThe road then continues in a southerly direction, passing close to the town of [[Wigton]]. A staggered crossroads at the section provides access to Wigton and also the [[B5305 road|B5305]] towards [[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]]. The twin transmitters of [[Caldbeck]] and [[Sandale transmitting station|Sandale]] are visible close to this section of the road.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nThe next section follows a meandering path through several hamlets, before reaching the village of [[Bothel, Cumbria|Bothel]], where the [[A591]] from [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]] terminates. The road then passes the site of the former Moota motel. This section of the route is notable for the two long straight sections, which are fairly rare on the A595. The road once again meanders until the roundabout junction with the [[A594 road (Cumbria)|A594]] road from [[Cockermouth]] to [[Maryport]]. It then passes over the [[River Derwent, Cumbria|River Derwent]] via Papcastle Bridge before turning west and becoming the part of the [[A66 road (England)|A66]] until Little Clifton. During the [[2009 Great Britain and Ireland floods|2009 Cumbrian floods]], the Papcastle bridge was briefly closed, essentially splitting [[West Cumbria]] in two. With bridge collapses and damage on the nearby [[A596]], and a road closure on the [[A591]], the only passable route to anywhere north of the River Derwent was via the [[A66 road|A66]] and [[M6 motorway|M6]] to [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]] - a diversion of over {{convert|90|mi}}.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nAt this point the road turns towards Lillyhall, passing through Lillyhall Industrial Estate and joining the [[Distington]] bypass, constructed in 2008. This section of road is notable as it is the only section of national speed limit dual carriageway along the whole length of the road. The end of the dual carriageway section is a roundabout junction near [[Lowca]] rejoining the original A595 road. It is then a short journey along the coast to the edge of [[Whitehaven]].<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\n===Southern section===\nThe road passes through Loop Road North & Loop Road South in [[Whitehaven]] passing the suburbs of the Highlands, Hill Crest and [[Hensingham]]. It forms the [[Hensingham]] bypass at this section, constructed in the 1980s to ease the passage of construction traffic to [[Sellafield]] through a particularly narrow and busy section of the road. It then passes close to [[West Cumberland Hospital]] and West Lakes Science & Technology Park. There is a campaign to build a bypass from the recently built [[Distington]] Bypass to this part of the A595 to ease congestion in the [[Whitehaven]] area.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nAfter this, the road the passes near to [[Moor Row]] and through the centre of Bigrigg, before heading downhill to [[Egremont, Cumbria|Egremont]]. The northbound side of the road here was upgraded in the 1980s to provide an extra uphill lane for overtaking due to the steep gradient. At the bottom of the hill the roundabout forms a junction with the B5086 which gives access to [[Cleator Moor]] and eventually [[Cockermouth]].<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nThe A595 the forms the [[Egremont, Cumbria|Egremont]] bypass. This bypass was built in the early '90s as a result of an investment by [[BNFL]] in local infrastructure following the siting of the THORP reprocessing plant at [[Sellafield]]. Prior to the bypass, the A595 originally passed right through the middle of town of Egremont. Once past the village of Thornhill, you can then see the sprawling [[Sellafield]] nuclear site. Twin cooling towers previously dominated the skyline here. However, they were demolished in 2007.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nThe road then passes [[Beckermet]] and [[Calder Bridge]], junctions here give access to the [[Sellafield]] site. From Calder Bridge, the A595 forms the boundary of the [[Lake District National Park]], going between the villages of [[Seascale]] and [[Gosforth, Cumbria|Gosforth]]. It enters the national park at the bridge over the [[River Irt]] at Holmrook and continues past the village of [[Ravenglass]], then passes through [[Waberthwaite, Cumbria|Waberthwaite]] and [[Bootle, Cumbria|Bootle]] and round the foot of [[Black Combe]].<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" /><ref name=\"OS OL6\">{{cite map | title = The English Lakes South-Western Area: OL6|date = March 2015|scale = 1:25,000|series = OS Explorer|publisher = [[Ordnance Survey]]}}</ref>\n\nAt Whicham the road has a [[List of road-related terminology#T|TOTSO]] (turn off to stay on) junction with the [[A5093 road|A5093]], close to the town of [[Millom]], taking a north-easterly route along Whicham Valley. For much of this stretch, the road is close to or is the boundary of the Lake District National Park. At [[Duddon Bridge]], the road crosses the river Duddon which previously marked the boundary of the historic county of [[Cumberland]] and [[Lancashire]]. The road then turns towards [[Broughton-in-Furness]] and used to go through it but now diverts via Foxfield before turning north to rejoin its old route, then once again turning south. At Grizebeck, the [[A5092 road|A5092]] then branches off the road to connect with the [[A590]] forming another TOTSO. This is also the point at which the A595 ceases to be the boundary to the Lake District National Park.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />{{r|OS OL6}}\n\nThe road finally passes through [[Kirkby-in-Furness]], Ireleth and [[Askam-in-Furness]] before terminating {{convert|1.8|mi}} further south at Elliscales roundabout where it crosses the Dalton bypass [[A590]].\n\nThe last section of the road is particularly narrow and even passes through a farmyard.<ref>{{cite news|title=Residents asked how to improve the A595 |url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/residents-asked-how-to-improve-the-a595-1.741880? |accessdate=20 January 2011 |newspaper=North West Evening Mail |date=3 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005172450/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/residents-asked-how-to-improve-the-a595-1.741880 |archivedate=5 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Safety==\n\nThe road, along with the A66, is considered to be the most dangerous road in Cumbria.<ref>[http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/1.143669 Times & Star - Detrunked A595 more dangerous] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719185210/http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/1.143669 |date=19 July 2011 }}</ref> There are several accident blackspots along the length of the road. One of the most notable is a stretch known as Moota, which is regularly the scene of fatal accidents.<ref>[http://newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.223747 News & Star - Cyclist badly hurt in A595 crash] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823054435/http://newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.223747 |date=23 August 2011 }}</ref> The northern section was formerly a trunk road, but until the recent completion of the [[Distington]] Bypass it had only one small section of dual carriageway. The southern section of the road around New Mill does not have a secondary route. When this section is closed due to an accident or roadworks, the detour routes are via Wrynose and Hardknott mountain passes for cars, and via the M6 J40 for HGVs, the latter being a detour of {{convert|120|mi}}.<ref>[http://www.whitehavennews.co.uk/news/1.272246 Whitehaven News - A595 closure causes major disruption] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924124635/http://www.whitehavennews.co.uk/news/1.272246 |date=24 September 2011 }}</ref> The poor safety record of the road is highlighted by signs erected on the route stating \"1245 casualties in 5 years\".\n\n==Road schemes==\n\n===Carlisle Northern Development Route (A689)===\nThe '''Carlisle Northern Development Route''' (CNDR) is a proposed {{convert|4|mi|adj=on}} long north-western [[bypass (road)|bypass]] of Carlisle, which would replace the existing A595 through the city (Wigton Road, Church Street, Bridge Street and Castle Way) and reduce congestion on the city's roads. The new road would be of single carriageway standard, with a number of [[roundabout]] junctions, as well as a new bridge over the [[River Eden, Cumbria|River Eden]]. The route would begin near Newby West (to the west of the city), before meeting the B5307 (the road to [[Abbeytown]]). Shortly afterwards it would cross over the River Eden, and curve round to the north of the Kingstown Industrial Estate, and terminate at Junction 44 of the [[M6 motorway]].\n\nThe development of the route has suffered several setbacks. In August 2008 a discovery of a [[great crested newt]] colony led to a delay in the start of the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.216566 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510071558/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.216566 |archivedate=10 May 2009 |df=dmy }} - Great crested newts delay Carlisle bypass</ref> In February 2009 a potentially important [[Stone Age]] find was discovered during surveying work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/stone_age_finds_delay_carlisle_bypass_again_1_519575?referrerPath%3Dhome%2Fnews_star_search_results_page_2_1962 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504095145/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/stone_age_finds_delay_carlisle_bypass_again_1_519575?referrerPath=home%2Fnews_star_search_results_page_2_1962 |archivedate=4 May 2009 |df=dmy }} - Stone Age find delays bypass again</ref> The most serious problem to face the development was the near collapse of the bank providing the funds under a [[private finance initiative]]. Belgian bank [[Dexia]] was involved in a \u00a35 billion bailout during the [[Credit Crunch]]. A consortium of banks later stepped in to provide the funding, and construction is currently underway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/stone_age_finds_delay_carlisle_bypass_again_1_519575?referrerPath%3Dhome%2Fnews_star_search_results_page_2_1962 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504095145/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/stone_age_finds_delay_carlisle_bypass_again_1_519575?referrerPath=home%2Fnews_star_search_results_page_2_1962 |archivedate=4 May 2009 |df=dmy }} Funding problems for bypass</ref>\nThe bypass opened in Spring 2012.\n\n===Parton to Lillyhall improvements===\n\nThe Parton to Lillyhall bypass was opened in December 2008 after a period of 18 months construction. The road runs from the junction with the [[A596 road|A596]] at Lillyhall to a new junction created close to the A595 junction for Lowca. The new road replaces a winding, narrow section of the A595 which passed through the village of Distington. Prior to this project the A595 was considered for de-trunking, meaning the scheme would have become the responsibility of Cumbria County Council. However, it was not de-trunked, and has instead been listed in the government's [https://web.archive.org/web/20070527191510/http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/projects/7393.aspx Targeted Programme of Improvements].\n\n===Whitehaven Eastern Relief Road===\n\n[[Copeland (UK Parliament constituency)|Copeland]] MP [[Jamie Reed]] and [[Cumbria]] County Council leader Stewart Young have been pressing the UK government for an eastern relief road to take the A595 away from a bottleneck through the town of [[Whitehaven]]. The proposed route would connect with recent Parton to Lillyhall bypass, it would then pass to the east of the town, past the newly proposed replacement for West Cumberland Hospital, then finally passing West Lakes Science & Technology Park before joining the current A595 south of [[Whitehaven]]. Plans are being drawn up as part of the Energy Coast masterplan to regenerate West Cumbria.<ref>[http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.509367 News & Star - Plan for \u00a340 million Whitehaven bypass] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207152755/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.509367 |date=7 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n*[http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/roadlists/r10/notes.php?number=A595 SABRE Roads page on A595]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070901135705/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/news/2004/october/10_12_2004-111512-AM.asp Cumbria County Council - Carlisle Northern Development Route a step nearer]\n*[http://www.cbrd.co.uk/futures/bypass/a595b.shtml CBRD page on A595 Carlisle Northern Relief Road]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060529023218/http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/projects/5130.aspx Highways Agency - A595 Parton to Lillyhall improvements]\n\n{{GB A road zone 5}}\n\n{{coord|54.5108|-3.5499|dim:100000_region:GB|display=title|name=A595 road}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:5-0595}}\n[[Category:Roads in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Furness]]\n[[Category:Transport in Barrow-in-Furness]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=595\n|length_mi=\n|direction_a= North\n|terminus_a = [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]]\n|direction_b= South\n|terminus_b = [[Dalton-in-Furness]]<br>{{coord|54.1639|-3.1888|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=A595 road (southern end)}}\n|junction   = {{jct|country=GBR|A|7|noshield1=|nolink1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|596|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|591|name1= }}<br />[[File:UK road A594.PNG|50px|alt=A594]] [[A594 road (Cumbria)|A594 road]]<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|5086|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|66|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|597|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|5094|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|5093|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|5093|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|593|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|5092|name1= }}<br />{{jct|country=GBR|A|590|name1= }}\n|destinations= [[Workington]]<br>[[Whitehaven]]<br>[[Barrow-in-Furness]]\n}}\n\nThe '''A595''' is a [[primary route]] in [[Cumbria]], in [[Northern England]] that starts in [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], passes through [[Whitehaven]] and goes close to [[Workington]], [[Cockermouth]] and [[Wigton]]. It passes [[Sellafield]] and [[Ravenglass]] before ending at the [[Dalton-in-Furness]] by-pass, in southern Cumbria, where it joins the [[A590 road|A590]] trunk road. The road is mostly [[single carriageway]], apart from in central Carlisle, where it passes the [[Carlisle Castle|castle]] as a busy [[dual carriageway]] road named Castle Way, and prior to that as Bridge Street and Church Street, where it passes close to the [[McVitie's]] or [[Carr's]] [[biscuit]] factory. The Lillyhall bypass is also dual carriageway.\n\nThe road in the [[Whitehaven]] area was laid out in the 1930s and the A595 was designated a trunk route in 1946. It was detrunked in 1998, apart from an {{Convert|18|mi|adj=on}} section between Little Clifton and [[Calder Bridge]]. This section represents the route from [[Sellafield]] to the [[A66 road (England)|A66]].\n\nAt Duddon Bridge and at Dove Ford near Grizebeck the road passes through farmyards.\n\n==Route==\n\n===Northern section===\nThe {{convert|85|mi|adj=on}} long A595 is also known as the Cumbrian Coast Road despite much of the road following in an inland route. Starting at the Hardwicke Circus roundabout junction with the [[A7 road (Great Britain)|A7]] in [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], it forms a short section of dual carriageway known as Castle Way. This section passes [[Carlisle Castle]] and [[Tullie House]]. Prior to the construction of Castle Way, the road was split in 2 at this section. It then continues over Caldew Bridge to a thoroughfare called Caldewgate, before arriving at a roundabout close to the [[McVitie's]] factory in the city centre. It then follows the route of Wigton Road through the district of Morton, before reaching the outer boundary of Carlisle. At this point it passes the start point of the Carlisle Northern Development Route, where construction work commenced in 2009. This route is the A689.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\">http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=A595</ref> A further roundabout was constructed in 2011 around 1 mile south of Carlisle in anticipation of increased traffic for a nearby garden centre development.\n\nThe route continues in a south-westerly direction until it reaches a roundabout on the outskirts of [[Thursby]] at a junction with [[A596 road|A596]]. The roads previously met in the centre of the village of Thursby, before the construction of the Thursby bypass in the 1980s. The A595 runs largely parallel to [[A596]], before the [[A596]] terminates in Workington.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nThe road then continues in a southerly direction, passing close to the town of [[Wigton]]. A staggered crossroads at the section provides access to Wigton and also the [[B5305 road|B5305]] towards [[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]]. The twin transmitters of [[Caldbeck]] and [[Sandale transmitting station|Sandale]] are visible close to this section of the road.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nThe next section follows a meandering path through several hamlets, before reaching the village of [[Bothel, Cumbria|Bothel]], where the [[A591]] from [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]] terminates. The road then passes the site of the former Moota motel. This section of the route is notable for the two long straight sections, which are fairly rare on the A595. The road once again meanders until the roundabout junction with the [[A594 road (Cumbria)|A594]] road from [[Cockermouth]] to [[Maryport]]. It then passes over the [[River Derwent, Cumbria|River Derwent]] via Papcastle Bridge before turning west and becoming the part of the [[A66 road (England)|A66]] until Little Clifton. During the [[2009 Great Britain and Ireland floods|2009 Cumbrian floods]], the Papcastle bridge was briefly closed, essentially splitting [[West Cumbria]] in two. With bridge collapses and damage on the nearby [[A596]], and a road closure on the [[A591]], the only passable route to anywhere north of the River Derwent was via the [[A66 road|A66]] and [[M6 motorway|M6]] to [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]] - a diversion of over {{convert|90|mi}}.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nAt this point the road turns towards Lillyhall, passing through Lillyhall Industrial Estate and joining the [[Distington]] bypass, constructed in 2008. This section of road is notable as it is the only section of national speed limit dual carriageway along the whole length of the road. The end of the dual carriageway section is a roundabout junction near [[Lowca]] rejoining the original A595 road. It is then a short journey along the coast to the edge of [[Whitehaven]].<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\n===Southern section===\nThe road passes through Loop Road North & Loop Road South in [[Whitehaven]] passing the suburbs of the Highlands, Hill Crest and [[Hensingham]]. It forms the [[Hensingham]] bypass at this section, constructed in the 1980s to ease the passage of construction traffic to [[Sellafield]] through a particularly narrow and busy section of the road. It then passes close to [[West Cumberland Hospital]] and West Lakes Science & Technology Park. There is a campaign to build a bypass from the recently built [[Distington]] Bypass to this part of the A595 to ease congestion in the [[Whitehaven]] area.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nAfter this, the road the passes near to [[Moor Row]] and through the centre of Bigrigg, before heading downhill to [[Egremont, Cumbria|Egremont]]. The northbound side of the road here was upgraded in the 1980s to provide an extra uphill lane for overtaking due to the steep gradient. At the bottom of the hill the roundabout forms a junction with the B5086 which gives access to [[Cleator Moor]] and eventually [[Cockermouth]].<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nThe A595 the forms the [[Egremont, Cumbria|Egremont]] bypass. This bypass was built in the early '90s as a result of an investment by [[BNFL]] in local infrastructure following the siting of the THORP reprocessing plant at [[Sellafield]]. Prior to the bypass, the A595 originally passed right through the middle of town of Egremont. Once past the village of Thornhill, you can then see the sprawling [[Sellafield]] nuclear site. Twin cooling towers previously dominated the skyline here. However, they were demolished in 2007.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />\n\nThe road then passes [[Beckermet]] and [[Calder Bridge]], junctions here give access to the [[Sellafield]] site. From Calder Bridge, the A595 forms the boundary of the [[Lake District National Park]], going between the villages of [[Seascale]] and [[Gosforth, Cumbria|Gosforth]]. It enters the national park at the bridge over the [[River Irt]] at Holmrook and continues past the village of [[Ravenglass]], then passes through [[Waberthwaite, Cumbria|Waberthwaite]] and [[Bootle, Cumbria|Bootle]] and round the foot of [[Black Combe]].<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" /><ref name=\"OS OL6\">{{cite map | title = The English Lakes South-Western Area: OL6|date = March 2015|scale = 1:25,000|series = OS Explorer|publisher = [[Ordnance Survey]]}}</ref>\n\nAt Whicham the road has a [[List of road-related terminology#T|TOTSO]] (turn off to stay on) junction with the [[A5093 road|A5093]], close to the town of [[Millom]], taking a north-easterly route along Whicham Valley. For much of this stretch, the road is close to or is the boundary of the Lake District National Park. At [[Duddon Bridge]], the road crosses the river Duddon which previously marked the boundary of the historic county of [[Cumberland]] and [[Lancashire]]. The road then turns towards [[Broughton-in-Furness]] and used to go through it but now diverts via Foxfield before turning north to rejoin its old route, then once again turning south. At Grizebeck, the [[A5092 road|A5092]] then branches off the road to connect with the [[A590]] forming another TOTSO. This is also the point at which the A595 ceases to be the boundary to the Lake District National Park.<ref name=\"sabre-roads\" />{{r|OS OL6}}\n\nThe road finally passes through [[Kirkby-in-Furness]], Ireleth and [[Askam-in-Furness]] before terminating {{convert|1.8|mi}} further south at Elliscales roundabout where it crosses the Dalton bypass [[A590]].\n\nThe last section of the road is particularly narrow and even passes through a farmyard.<ref>{{cite news|title=Residents asked how to improve the A595 |url=http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/residents-asked-how-to-improve-the-a595-1.741880? |accessdate=20 January 2011 |newspaper=North West Evening Mail |date=3 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005172450/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/news/residents-asked-how-to-improve-the-a595-1.741880 |archivedate=5 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Safety==\n\nThe road, along with the A66, is considered to be the most dangerous road in Cumbria.<ref>[http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/1.143669 Times & Star - Detrunked A595 more dangerous] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719185210/http://www.timesandstar.co.uk/1.143669 |date=19 July 2011 }}</ref> There are several accident blackspots along the length of the road. One of the most notable is a stretch known as Moota, which is regularly the scene of fatal accidents.<ref>[http://newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.223747 News & Star - Cyclist badly hurt in A595 crash] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823054435/http://newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.223747 |date=23 August 2011 }}</ref> The northern section was formerly a trunk road, but until the recent completion of the [[Distington]] Bypass it had only one small section of dual carriageway. The southern section of the road around New Mill does not have a secondary route. When this section is closed due to an accident or roadworks, the detour routes are via Wrynose and Hardknott mountain passes for cars, and via the M6 J40 for HGVs, the latter being a detour of {{convert|120|mi}}.<ref>[http://www.whitehavennews.co.uk/news/1.272246 Whitehaven News - A595 closure causes major disruption] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924124635/http://www.whitehavennews.co.uk/news/1.272246 |date=24 September 2011 }}</ref> The poor safety record of the road is highlighted by signs erected on the route stating \"1245 casualties in 5 years\".\n\n==Road schemes==\n\n===Carlisle Northern Development Route (A689)===\nThe '''Carlisle Northern Development Route''' (CNDR) is a proposed {{convert|4|mi|adj=on}} long north-western [[bypass (road)|bypass]] of Carlisle, which would replace the existing A595 through the city (Wigton Road, Church Street, Bridge Street and Castle Way) and reduce congestion on the city's roads. The new road would be of single carriageway standard, with a number of [[roundabout]] junctions, as well as a new bridge over the [[River Eden, Cumbria|River Eden]]. The route would begin near Newby West (to the west of the city), before meeting the B5307 (the road to [[Abbeytown]]). Shortly afterwards it would cross over the River Eden, and curve round to the north of the Kingstown Industrial Estate, and terminate at Junction 44 of the [[M6 motorway]].\n\nThe development of the route has suffered several setbacks. In August 2008 a discovery of a [[great crested newt]] colony led to a delay in the start of the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.216566 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510071558/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.216566 |archivedate=10 May 2009 |df=dmy }} - Great crested newts delay Carlisle bypass</ref> In February 2009 a potentially important [[Stone Age]] find was discovered during surveying work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/stone_age_finds_delay_carlisle_bypass_again_1_519575?referrerPath%3Dhome%2Fnews_star_search_results_page_2_1962 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504095145/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/stone_age_finds_delay_carlisle_bypass_again_1_519575?referrerPath=home%2Fnews_star_search_results_page_2_1962 |archivedate=4 May 2009 |df=dmy }} - Stone Age find delays bypass again</ref> The most serious problem to face the development was the near collapse of the bank providing the funds under a [[private finance initiative]]. Belgian bank [[Dexia]] was involved in a \u00a35 billion bailout during the [[Credit Crunch]]. A consortium of banks later stepped in to provide the funding, and construction is currently underway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/stone_age_finds_delay_carlisle_bypass_again_1_519575?referrerPath%3Dhome%2Fnews_star_search_results_page_2_1962 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504095145/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/stone_age_finds_delay_carlisle_bypass_again_1_519575?referrerPath=home%2Fnews_star_search_results_page_2_1962 |archivedate=4 May 2009 |df=dmy }} Funding problems for bypass</ref>\nThe bypass opened in Spring 2012.\n\n===Parton to Lillyhall improvements===\n\nThe Parton to Lillyhall bypass was opened in December 2008 after a period of 18 months construction. The road runs from the junction with the [[A596 road|A596]] at Lillyhall to a new junction created close to the A595 junction for Lowca. The new road replaces a winding, narrow section of the A595 which passed through the village of Distington. Prior to this project the A595 was considered for de-trunking, meaning the scheme would have become the responsibility of Cumbria County Council. However, it was not de-trunked, and has instead been listed in the government's [https://web.archive.org/web/20070527191510/http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/projects/7393.aspx Targeted Programme of Improvements].\n\n===Whitehaven Eastern Relief Road===\n\n[[Copeland (UK Parliament constituency)|Copeland]] MP [[Jamie Reed]] and [[Cumbria]] County Council leader Stewart Young have been pressing the UK government for an eastern relief road to take the A595 away from a bottleneck through the town of [[Whitehaven]]. The proposed route would connect with recent Parton to Lillyhall bypass, it would then pass to the east of the town, past the newly proposed replacement for West Cumberland Hospital, then finally passing West Lakes Science & Technology Park before joining the current A595 south of [[Whitehaven]]. Plans are being drawn up as part of the Energy Coast masterplan to regenerate West Cumbria.<ref>[http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.509367 News & Star - Plan for \u00a340 million Whitehaven bypass] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207152755/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/1.509367 |date=7 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n*[http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/roadlists/r10/notes.php?number=A595 SABRE Roads page on A595]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070901135705/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/news/2004/october/10_12_2004-111512-AM.asp Cumbria County Council - Carlisle Northern Development Route a step nearer]\n*[http://www.cbrd.co.uk/futures/bypass/a595b.shtml CBRD page on A595 Carlisle Northern Relief Road]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060529023218/http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/projects/5130.aspx Highways Agency - A595 Parton to Lillyhall improvements]\n\n{{GB A road zone 5}}\n\n{{coord|54.5108|-3.5499|dim:100000_region:GB|display=title|name=A595 road}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:5-0595}}\n[[Category:Roads in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Furness]]\n[[Category:Transport in Barrow-in-Furness]]\n", "name_user": "Rschen7754", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File:UK road A594.PNG\u2192File:UK road A594.svgsvg", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A595_road"}
